<h1>@HI{{te}}-form cause</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vte{{}}, ...
<li> @Vnaistem{{}}@HI{{nakute}}, ...
<li> @Aistem{{}}@HI{{kute}}, ...
<li> @Anastem{{}}@HI{{de}}, ...
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
The subordinate clause presents a cause and the main clause states the consequence produced by that cause. Note that
this pattern, unlike @HI{{kara}} has many restrictions on its usage.
</p>

<p>
The contents of the main clause must not contain volition.
</p>

<p>
The main clause often contains:
<ul>
<li> verbs and adjectives that express feelings
<li> potential verbs to express states
<li> situations in the past
</ul>
</p>

<p>
The subordinate clause must occur chronologically before the main clause. So it is not allowed, for example,
for the subordinate clause to represent a future event and the main clause to represent an event in the present.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{house^tribe}}ni @EM{{@KJ{{meeting}}enakute}}, @KJ{{loneliness}}shiidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I miss my family.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{tale}}ga @EM{{@KJ{{duplicate^miscellaneous}}de}}, yoku wakarimasendeshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The story was complicated so I could not understand it well.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
